<br>
WARNING: This stuff feeds an army when finished, so you will likely have Chili for 3 or 4 days, and well you'll have something else too if done correctly <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Here is what you need<br>
<br>
1 Container of chili powder (The big spice jar , not that crappy pre mixxed BS You can get these for like $.50 not the baby jar) <br>
<br>
1 Container of Ground Red Pepper (Same size as the chili powder)<br>
<br>
1 Container of Crushed Red pepper<br>
<br>
2 lbs chili meat<br>
<br>
1 LARGE white onion.<br>
<br>
1 Large garlic bulb<br>
<br>
4 Tomatoes<br>
<br>
10 FRESH chili peppers<br>
<br>
1 lb of dried beans... not those damn kidney beans either, when you are done you shouldnt be able to tell theres beans in your chili at all...<br>
<br>
1 spig of cilantro<br>
<br>
<br>
PREP:<br>
<br>
OK making this takes ALL DAY...<br>
<br>
EARLY in the morning.. like 9 AM Start your beans boiling, add salt, pepper, and ground red pepper to the water, these should be brought to a boil and then reduce the heat a bit and let them simmer for 4 hours. Reduce the heat more when the beans are soft. Maybe add a half a bottle of beer when your water level has dropped some.<br>
<br>
Dice all your vegtables<br>
<br>
time passes .. 4 hours later<br>
<br>
OK your beans are well cooked now, or should be.. <br>
<br>
Drain all the water and put them in a large slow cooker or a BIG stock pot<br>
<br>
add 1/2 of all your veggies now, 2 Cans of tomato sauce and 1 can of tomato paste. and some crushed red pepper, ground red pepper, and 1/4 jar of chili powder. 1.5 cans of water or beer if you prefer<br>
<br>
Brown your meat, use about a quarter of the jar of ground red pepper and half the jar of chili powder<br>
<br>
<br>
add the meat, and cook 4 hours<br>
<br>
add the rest of your veggies, more chili powder pepper salt , red pepper, crushed and ground.. basically everything you added before. Now let this cook as long as you can stand it.. add some water if needed... usually 4 more hours would be good, 6 is better.<br>
<br>
Don't forget your resist gear when serving this.<br>
